A. Sustained Use Discount (SUD)

How it works: Applied automatically. No upfront payment or reservation needed.
Tiered Discount: The more you run a specific VM within a month, the higher the discount.

If you run a VM for 25% of the month -> ~20% discount.
If you run for 50% -> ~25% discount.
If you run for 100% (whole month) -> ~30% max discount.

Scope: Applies only to vCPU and Memory costs. License fees (e.g., Windows OS) are NOT discounted.
Eligible Families: General Purpose (N2, N2D) and Compute Optimized get up to 20-30% max. Memory Optimized and Accelerator families have different limits.

Limitations:

Does not apply to VMs created via App Engine or GKE.
Does not apply to certain shared-core machine types (f1-micro, e2-micro).

B. Committed Use Discount (CUD)

How it works: You commit to a 1-year or 3-year term. Pay a fixed monthly price regardless of actual usage.
Benefit: Much higher discounts (up to 57%-70% depending on machine family). Memory Optimized types get the highest (70%).
Key Point: Unlike AWS Reserved Instances, no upfront payment is required in GCP. You just pay the discounted monthly bill.

Limitations:

Free Trial accounts (with no payment history) are not eligible.
Cannot be applied to Preemptible VMs.
Commitment is locked; you cannot cancel or downgrade mid-term.
The commitment is bound to a specific project (not transferable).

C. Preemptible VMs (Spot VMs)

Concept: GCP sells its idle/unused data center capacity at a massive discount (up to 91%).

Analogy:

A train leaves at 9 AM. If a seat is empty, the railway offers it at 50% off just to fill it.
Hotels offer huge discounts at night because empty rooms generate zero revenue.
Similarly, GCP rents out idle hardware at a steep discount.

Key Risks & Rules:

GCP can terminate your VM anytime it needs the capacity back (with a 30-second warning).

Maximum runtime: 24 hours. The VM is automatically stopped/killed after 24 hours.
No SLA: Google provides no guarantee of availability.
No charge if Google terminates the VM in the first minute.
No Live Migration: Preemptible VMs cannot be migrated to regular VMs and vice versa.

Free Trial Credits cannot be used to purchase Preemptible VMs.
Use Case: Stateless, fault-tolerant batch processing, rendering jobs, testing workloads. Never use for production databases.

2. Storage Options for Compute Engine
When you create a VM, you attach disks to it. GCP offers Block Storage (Persistent Disks) and Object Storage.

Storage Types Diagram:

STORAGE FOR COMPUTE ENGINE
├── BLOCK STORAGE (Bootable - OS can be installed)
│   ├── 1. Persistent Disk Standard (HDD - Low cost)
│   ├── 2. Persistent Disk Balanced (SSD - Mid-tier)
│   ├── 3. Persistent Disk Performance (SSD - High IOPS)
│   └── 4. Persistent Disk Extreme (SSD - Highest IOPS, Min 500GB)
│
├── LOCAL STORAGE (Temporary)
│   └── Local SSD (Physically attached, ephemeral, high speed)
│
└── OBJECT STORAGE (Not Bootable - No OS)
    └── Cloud Storage (Buckets - Data storage/archival)

A. Persistent Disks (Block Storage)
Definition: Network-attached durable storage. Data persists even if the VM is deleted.

Types (4 variants):

Standard: HDD-based. Cheapest, lowest IOPS.
Balanced: SSD-based. Cost-effective, medium performance.
Performance (SSD): Higher IOPS for databases and enterprise apps.
Extreme: Highest IOPS/Throughput. Minimum 500GB required. For SAP HANA, heavy transactional workloads.

Key Features:

Bootable: All 4 types can be used as a boot disk.
Resizing: You can only increase disk size, never decrease it.
Performance Scaling: IOPS and throughput scale automatically with the disk size.

Zonal vs Regional:

Zonal: Data in a single zone. Cost-effective.
Regional: Data replicated synchronously to two zones within a region. Provides automatic failover (if one zone fails, the disk survives).

B. Local SSDs (Ephemeral Storage)
Definition: Directly attached physical storage located on the same hardware rack as the VM.
Benefit: Extremely high IOPS and low latency.
Critical Drawback: Data is ephemeral (temporary) . It is wiped completely when the VM is stopped or terminated.

Reason: When you stop a VM, Google reclaims the physical resources. When you start it again, it might run on a different physical host. The Local SSD stays with the old host; you get a fresh one on the new host.

Use Case: Scratch space, temporary caches, high-speed processing where data loss is acceptable. Never store critical data.
